Part II: Homework Questions

Problem 1

In an experiment to investigate the effect of color of paper (blue=0, green=1) on response rates for questionnaires distributed by the ``windshield method’’ in supermarket parking lots, 26 representative supermarket parking lots were chosen in a metropolitan area. Blue questionnaires were randomly assigned to 9 lots, green questionnaires were randomly assigned to 10 lots. It has been suggested to the investigator that size of parking lot might be a useful variable, so they decided to use it as a continuous predictor. The response is the average response rates.

questionnaires = read.csv("questionnaire.csv", header=TRUE, sep=",")
head(questionnaires)
##   rate color lot.size
## 1   28  blue      300
## 2   26  blue      381
## 3   31  blue      226
## 4   27  blue      350
## 5   35  blue      100
## 6   29  blue      252
  1. State
    1. the regression line that corresponds to the blue questionnaires.
    2. the regression line that corresponds to the green questionnaires.

    2. The full model that we fit is \[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \; size + \beta_2 \; color + \beta_3 size*color + \varepsilon \]

    model.full = lm(rate ~ lot.size*color, data=questionnaires)
summary(model.full)
    ## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = rate ~ lot.size * color, data = questionnaires)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -5.6036 -1.1694  0.3028  1.2939  4.0309 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                      Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)         33.669361   2.306804  14.596 2.85e-10 ***
## lot.size            -0.019907   0.009189  -2.167   0.0468 *  
## colorgreen           1.660979   3.422258   0.485   0.6344    
## lot.size:colorgreen  0.002003   0.012136   0.165   0.8711    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 2.467 on 15 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:   0.41,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.292 
## F-statistic: 3.475 on 3 and 15 DF,  p-value: 0.04282

    Without looking at the statistical significance of the terms, we have the following two fitted regression lines: \[\text{Blue}: rate = 33.67 - 0.02\, size \] \[\text{Green}: rate = (33.67+1.66) + (- 0.02 + 0.002) \,size = 35.33 - 0.018\, size\]

  2. Test whether or not the interaction term is statistically significant. State the hypotheses, decision rule and conclusion.

    We want to perform the following hypothesis test: \[ \begin{cases} & H_0: \beta_{3} = 0\\ & H_{\alpha}: \beta_{3} \neq 0 \end{cases} \] We can also formulate it as \[ \begin{cases} & H_0: rate ~ size + color\\ & H_{\alpha}: rate ~ size + color + size*color \end{cases} \]

    model.red1 = lm(rate ~ lot.size + color, data = questionnaires)
anova(model.red1, model.full)
    ## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: rate ~ lot.size + color
## Model 2: rate ~ lot.size * color
##   Res.Df    RSS Df Sum of Sq      F Pr(>F)
## 1     16 91.458                           
## 2     15 91.293  1    0.1658 0.0272 0.8711
    Based on the p-value=0.87 we conclude that the interaction term is not statistically significant.

  3. Does the response rate vary according to the questionnaire color? Justify your answer.

    Since the interaction term is not statistically significant, we can remove it from the model. So, this question essentially asks us to test for the color factor. The hypothesis formulates as follows:

    \[ \begin{cases} & H_0: rate ~ size \\ & H_{\alpha}: rate ~ size + color \end{cases} \] 
    4. model.red2 = lm(rate ~ lot.size, data = questionnaires)
anova(model.red2, model.red1)
    ## Analysis of Variance Table
## 
## Model 1: rate ~ lot.size
## Model 2: rate ~ lot.size + color
##   Res.Df     RSS Df Sum of Sq     F  Pr(>F)  
## 1     17 111.511                             
## 2     16  91.458  1    20.052 3.508 0.07946 .
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
    Based on the p-value=0.079 > 0.05 we conclude that the color variable is not statistically significant, and therefore the response rate does not vary significantly according to the questionnaire color.

We have available the following predictors: AtBat, Hits, HmRun, Runs, RBI, Walks, Years, CAtBat, CHits, CHmRun, CRuns, CRBI, CWalks, League, Division, PutOuts, Assists, Errors. The data set is called Hitters and can be found in the ISLR library.

  1. What is the optimal number of parameters according to

    4. the BIC.

    Starting with the full model, we remove first the variable RBI, since this is the way that we will get the smallest BIC. In the next steps we remove the following variables in order: CHits, Years, CHmRun, HmRun, Errors, Runs, Assists, and CAtBat.
